Alert to pesticides ingested by children
A 10-year-old eats in a day 81 different chemicals, according to a study released Wednesday by the association Generations Futures (former Movement for Rights and the respect of future generations).
The association, which warns that its results "have no statistically significant value in the light of the low number of samples analyzed, but are illustrative of the problem dealt with," has purchased between July and September food usually eaten in four meals and a snack in one day by a child of a decade, the supermarkets in the'Oise and Paris.
These meals types, including the formal recommendations - five fruits and vegetables, dairy products and 1.5 litres of water per day - as well as snacks, were examined by laboratories in search of chemical substances, pesticides, heavy metals and other pollutants.
The death toll from the base is damning: 81 chemicals including 42 are classified as carcinogenic possible or probable and five substances classified as carcinogenic some and 37 substances that act as endocrine disrupters (PE), according to studies of several institutions such as the International Agency for Research on Cancer.
"Even if, in almost all cases, the legal limits for each substance taken individually are not exceeded, it is clear in our investigation that the reality of consumer exposure to contaminants possibly carcinogenic and / or PE is worrying," said the association.
For breakfast, butter and milk tea containing more than a dozen possible cancer-causing residues and three proven carcinogenic as certain as well as nearly 20 residues that can disrupt the hormonal system.
The apple, imported from Brazil, planned as a snack by the study, presented traces of six chemicals including a fungicide yet banned in France.
Same thing for green beans from Kenya, included in the lunch, on which the study has detected traces of a powerful insecticide banned in the EU.
In addition, ground beef, canned tuna, and even the stick of bread and chewing gum were strewn with pesticides and other chemicals.
In tap water analysis revealed the presence of nitrates, chloroform.
For dinner, the salmon steak was the most "rich" with 34 chemical residues detected and even the plastic base used to heat the meal in the microwave was not free.
The final risk to the consumer of this "cocktails of contaminants" "is probably underestimated," according to the study.
The Alliance Europe Ecologie-Les Greens (EE-LV), meanwhile, has proposed "given the urgency of the situation" a moratorium on the use of pesticides, to stop "the increase in diseases of civilisation".
In July, a study by the European Food Safety Agency (EFSA) reported the presence of residues of 365 different pesticides identified in fruits and vegetables consumed in Europe, including 76 in grains.
